.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
.AL
.LI
Assume that the \*LLANG\*O environment variable is set to
\*Lfr_FR.ISO8859-1\*O and the \*LLC_MONETARY\*O environment variable
to \*Lfr_CA.ISO8859-1\*O. The following example shows results when
you enter the \*Llocale\*O command without flags:
.IP
.iS
% locale
.iE
.oS
LANG=fr_FR.ISO8859-1
LC_COLLATE="fr_FR.ISO8859-1"
LC_CTYPE="fr_FR.ISO8859-1"
LC_MONETARY="fr_CA.ISO8859-1"
LC_NUMERIC="fr_FR.ISO8859-1"
LC_TIME="fr_FR.ISO8859-1"
LC_MESSAGES="fr_FR.ISO8859-1"
LC_ALL=
.oE
.IP
The \*LLC_ALL\*O variable, if set, overrides the values of
other variables.
For example, if \*LLC_ALL\*O is set to
\*Len_US.ISO8859-1\*O,
the setting implies \*LLC_COLLATE=en_US.ISO8859-1\*O,
even if the \*LLC_COLLATE\*O environment variable is set to another locale.
.LI
In the following example, the \*Llocale\*O command retrieves the value of
the \*Ldecimal_point\*O delimiter for the current locale:
.IP
.iS
% \*Llocale -ck decimal_point\*O
.iE
.oS
LC_NUMERIC
decimal_point="."
.oE
